SergeySnegirev:
I'm really new to GitHub but I'd like to help. What should I do to help document the events? Unless, of course, directing me is a bigger liability than actually documenting the issue :)
. Hi,
I just ran into this issue and solved it. CSS Modal guys use the following technique to stop video when modal is closed (pseudocode): 
- on hide event: store iframe source into data-src attribute, then set src to empty string
- on show event: check if iframe source is empty, then restore it from data-src attribute

The problem is, they only planned for ONE video on the page, so they use the following selector to catch the iframe:     var $video = $('.semantic-content iframe'); 

Now we need to only catch the currently displayed video, so I tried to modify the selector to:
    var $video = $('.semantic-content.is-active iframe');

...but it didn't work, because "is-active" class is removed BEFORE the event is fired. So we have to iterate through all videos and stop all of them. I'm sure the code could be better, but here goes: 

```
  $(document)
  .on('cssmodal:hide', function () {
    var $video = $('.semantic-content iframe');
    var source;
    $video.each(function(){
      if ($(this).length > 0) {
        source = $(this).attr('src');
        $(this).attr('src', '');
     if ( source !== '' ) $(this).attr('data-src', source);
      }
    });
  })
  .on('cssmodal:show', function () {
    var $video = $('.semantic-content.is-active iframe');
    var dataSource = $video.attr('data-src');
    if ($video.length > 0 && dataSource !== '') {
      $video.attr('src', dataSource).attr('data-src', '');
    }
  });
```
. First of all, my solution above DIDN'T work. I am sorry for confusing you, Santiago. 
Now the good news is that I have a working solution (and I edited my above comment to include it). Please look at my comment above, again. 

Also, here's a working demo: http://intea.lv/september (there are videos under J and L).
